					<additions><p>F.1r: 2 seals (one dated 1184, Edward Smith Bahadur, year 11; i.e. 1770). This is very likely Edward Smith (d. 1830), secretary to Warren Hastings, Governor-General of India, 1774-85; Bonhams sold a Qur'an owned by Edward Smith <ref target="https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/23436/lot/30/">https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/23436/lot/30/</ref>. See also other seals at <ref target="https://blogs.bl.uk/asian-and-african/2017/02/some-british-islamic-style-seals-in-persian-manuscripts-from-india.html ">https://blogs.bl.uk/asian-and-african/2017/02/some-british-islamic-style-seals-in-persian-manuscripts-from-india.html</ref> and <ref target="https://blogs.bl.uk/asian-and-african/2014/03/performing-authority-the-islamic-seals-of-british-colonial-officers.html">https://blogs.bl.uk/asian-and-african/2014/03/performing-authority-the-islamic-seals-of-british-colonial-officers.html</ref>.</p> 
					</additions>
